segments.text: Okay, to be back at...
The greatest honor you've ever had is to be at A&M College and do the review.
Now, when was this?
In May of 1955, when I took the review.
That's one of the greatest honors I've ever had at A&M College.
Tell me about it.
Well, I was up there, and the commandant, I forget his name now, don't come to me,
told me that he wanted me to take that review.
And he instructed me on what to salute.
Of course, I was very kind to you with the salute, but I took the instruction from him because everybody has their own ground rules.
So I appeared there at the right time and took the review.
I was in uniform, a lot of people there, and they introduced me and all that.
That was quite an honor.
It was quite an honor after having thought back when that guy told you, don't you come on this campus, you're not allowed here.
Yeah, right.
And so then you came on as a general.
Well, that's all right.
But anyhow, as I say, I'm proud of A&M, I'm proud of the Marine Corps, I'm proud to love people.
See, if God just wanted you on this race, he's all powerful.
He'd let you run in.
What the hell are you going to do by yourself?
Anyhow.
Was there anything else that you think that we should talk about as far as your career or your life is concerned?
Or do you think we pretty well covered it?
Well, all you're interested in, you're not interested in sidebar stuff.
what you accomplish as a civilian.
You want that being an Aggie and in your service.
I think I've given it all to you, but if anything else comes, you know, there are a lot of things.
You take this ride business, that thing was something.
I hid, and when I told my commanding general that morning at 4 o'clock when he relieved my battalion, I commenced crying to him, saying, look, this is the first time I've ever been king.
And he told me, he said, you better get on and quit thinking about being a king in your battalion.
You've got a new job to do, and get on and get with it.
General Lawson, 4 o'clock in the morning.
So I went on and got with it and did his job.
They never had a Provo Mark with 47 people in the headquarters, stockades.
I had Army personnel, I had Navy personnel, Marine personnel.
It was a job.
Every now and then, I remember one time an officer came up there.
He'd been put on report by not having the rat guards on his ship when he landed.
He commenced telling me about he graduated the Naval Academy, never been on a report in his life, and all of that.
So I had to answer him.
I said, I didn't put you on a report.
You put yourself on a report.
I said, because back at Pearl Harbor, all those instructions are telling you how to get into these waters and what to do when you dock a ship.
So I didn't put you on any report.
You put yourself on a report.
What did he say to that?
He just hung his head and left.
That's a word to tell you, wasn't it?
Because those marines right down there with the damn camera, boom, boom, boom.
No ship guards.
What's the name of the ship?
Bring all the reports, bring it all in.
I can't do nothing but after it comes in.
Then there's another guy came in there.
He was charged with stealing photographic papers.
Because I never been on a report in my life.
I said, well, you goddamn stupid son of a gun.
Don't you realize that that's not your property?
Don't you realize that that belongs to the Air Force?
Well, I see everybody else doing it.
I said, but you got caught.
What do you say to that?
He didn't like it.
He didn't like getting caught.
Anderson, look, I appreciate you coming and all like that, and we'll keep in touch.
Okay, great.
If we feel about having another interview, just let me know.
Okay, thanks a lot, General.
But I've got to get my wife back in.
She's been in that hospital.
